Ford Go Bike System Data¶

by Gabriela Garcia¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike is a bike sharing service available in the San Francisco Bay area. Their service has been available in the San Francisco area since 2013, I will be exploring data about this bike sharing service from the year 2018. It is a public bike sharing system that is only available regionally.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data has been seperated into different datasets based on month. I am curious about how some of this data changes from month to month so I have decided to load in all of the 2018 datasets. These data sets contain information on individual ride instances from their customers. This information includes time data such as duration, time, and date. It also includes start and end location data from their various stations. There is also customer information, and bike ids associated to each ride.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in which stations are the most popular for starting and ending. I would like to further explore if these stations have popular start-end combination pairs. I am also interested in whether or not popular stations vary month by month. This will give me an idea about people traffic and what some popular routes for biking are. I am also interested in customer type but I am not sure how I will work that into my exploration yet.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Station Names will help me distinguish individual stations from each other, and which ones show up most frequently. The start and end station columns will help me understand instances of when these individual stations were starting or ending points for bikers. The monthly seperated data will allow me to know if there is any variance in this data from month to month.

Univariate Exploration¶

Now I will try to look at counts for each station occurance. It is important to me to keep this data seperated by month so that I can see the variance over time. First, I will look at the total counts per month to see if there are dramatic differences in popularity of this bike share service from month to month.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Seeing the difference in use of the bike share service from season to season really emphasized that I will need to account for that later. Since I want to compare which stations are popular from month to month it would be better to use relative values so that the popularity of the bike share in that month does not dissort the data. I was also suprised to see that the few most used stations we're used much more than the other stations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I decided to use relative values so that when I make comparisions of station popularity from month to month the difference in overall rides for any particular month would not disort the comparison.
